  "notes": "Tsonga (Xitsonga). Bantu language spoken in southern Mozambique, Limpopo and Mpumalanga (South Africa), Zimbabwe, and Eswatini. ~7 million speakers; official language of South Africa. KEY FEATURES: (1) FIVE-VOWEL SYSTEM: a/e/i/o/u; e=[ɛ], o=[ɔ]. (2) PRENASALIZED STOPS: mb/nd — phonemic word-initial sequences. (3) BREATHY RHOTIC: <rh> = [r̤] (breathy-voiced trill), contrastive with plain <r> = [r]. (4) LATERAL AFFRICATE: tl=[tɬ] (lateral affricate), phonemic. (5) LABIODENTAL AFFRICATE: bv=[bv], phonemic. (6) SIBILANT COMPLEX: x/xi=[ʃ], ts=[ts], dz=[dz]. (7) ASPIRATED STOPS: kh/ph/th = [kʰ/pʰ/tʰ], phonemic. (8) TONES: two-tone system (H/L), not marked in orthography. (9) SYLLABIC NASALS: m-/n- noun prefixes syllabic before consonants. Sources: Baumbach (1987) is the primary descriptive grammar.",
